1. PyClone - Dirichlet Process Mixture Model (DPMM)¶

In this problem, you should apply a collapsed Gibbs sampler in order to cluster mutations based on a Dirichlet Process Mixture Model (DPMM). The probabilistic model can, following the original publication, be described by the graphical model in Figure 1(a), where H is a Dirichlet Process (DP). We will instead use the graphical model in Figure 1(b), which yields the same distribution when equipped with distributions as follows,

\begin{align} \pi &\sim GEM(\alpha) \\ z_n &\sim \pi \\ \phi^k &\sim H_0 = Beta (a_0,a_1) \\ d^n &\sim Poisson(d_0) \\ b^n &\sim Bin (d^n , \phi^{Z_n}) \end{align}

where GEM (stands for Griffiths, Engen, and McCloskey) denotes the stick-breaking process.

1.2 Inference on DPMM¶

For the sake of simplicity, we will treat variables $d$ as observed in this section.

1.2.1 Collapsed Gibbs sampler¶

As exact analysis of DPMM is intractable, we use Gibbs sampling for inference. To implement a Gibbs sampler we need to derive the conditional distribution for the class assignments $z$. We mainly need the individual class assignment conditioned on the class assignments of all other objects and the data x, $p(z_n = k | z_{−n}, x)$, which can be expressed as, \begin{equation} p(z_n = k | z_{−n}, x) \propto p(z_n = k | z_{−n}) p(x_n | x_{-n} ,z_n = k, z_{-n}) \end{equation}

We will first focus on the first term $p(z_n = k | z_{−n})$.

Consider the finite mixture model, where K is fixed: \begin{equation} p(z_n = k | z_{−n}) = \int p(z_n = k | \pi) p(\pi | z_{−n}, \alpha) d\pi \end{equation} By construction the above equation corresponds to the posterior predictive for a multinomial distribution with a Dirichlet prior with parameter ($\alpha$ = ($\alpha$/K, . . . , $\alpha$/K)), which can be solved analytically \begin{equation} p(z_n = k | z_{−n}) = \frac {N_{-n,k}+ \frac{\alpha}{K}}{N -1 + \alpha} \end{equation} where $N_{−n,k}$ is the number of objects assigned to $k$th class excluding the $n$th object.

For infinite case (equivalent to the Chinese restaurant process), $K \rightarrow \infty $, \begin{equation} p(z_n = k | z_{−n}) = \bigg\{ \begin{array}{lr} \frac {N_{-n,k}}{N -1 + \alpha} \;\;\; \text{,if k has been seen before $N_{-n,k} > 0 $} \\ \frac {\alpha}{N -1 + \alpha} \;\;\; \text{,if k is a new cluster} \end{array} \end{equation}

Now, consider the second term $p(x_n | x_{-n} ,z_n = k, z_{-n})$.

If $k \in 1, ... , K$, then it is the posterior predictive distribution for cluster $k$ evaluated at point $x_n$,

\begin{align} p(x_n | x_{-n} ,z_n = k, z_{-n}) = BetaBinomial(x_n | d^n,a_0^k,a_1^k) \end{align}

where $a_0^k$ and $a_1^k$ are the posterior hyperparameters for the $k$th cluster,

\begin{align} a_0^k &= a_0 + \sum_{i=1}^N b^i \mathbf{1}[z_i = k] \\ a_1^k &= a_1 + \sum_{i=1}^N (d^i - b^i) \mathbf{1}[z_i = k] \end{align}

If $k$ is a new cluster, then it is the prior predictive distribution evaluated at point $x_n$,

\begin{align} p(x_n | x_{-n} ,z_n = k, z_{-n}) = BetaBinomial(x_n | d^n,a_0,a_1) \end{align}

where $a_0$ and $a_1$ are the prior hyperparameters.

Implement collapsed Gibbs sampler for this DPMM. Test it on synthetic data with the following values of the hyperparameters: $\alpha = 1$, $a_0 = a_1 = 1$, and $d_0 = 1000$. Provide a figure depicting accuracy of clustering.

Make sure to do the calculations in the logarithmic scale for numeric stability.

(Hint: You can write BetaBinomial distribution in terms of gamma functions. Check scipy.special.loggamma function.)

2. Particle Gibbs with Ancestral Sampling¶

Relevant resources:

  • Andrieu, Christophe, Arnaud Doucet, and Roman Holenstein. "Particle markov chain monte carlo methods." Journal of the Royal Statistical Society: Series B (Statistical Methodology) 72.3 (2010): 269-342.
  • Lindsten, Fredrik, Michael I. Jordan, and Thomas B. Schon. "Particle Gibbs with ancestor sampling." Journal of Machine Learning Research 15 (2014): 2145-2184.
  • Uppsala university's SMC course (see our lecture slides for refences).
  • Our lecture slides available on Canvas.

This is a follow-up task from Assigment 3. If you implemented the BPF, you will be able to reuse code from the last assignment (if you did not implement the BPF before, you get the chance to implement it here instead). There, you were asked to find the parameters, $\theta$, that most likely generated the observations, $y_{1:T}$ by evaluating $p(y_{1:T}|\theta)$ for different choices of $\theta$ (recall the grid search).

Here you will learn a more elegant method for inferring probable parameters: via a combination of particle filtering and MCMC, hence termed PMCMC. This approach was first proposed by Andrieu et al. (in the first item above). You are asked to first implement the particle Gibbs (PG) method, which we discussed in the lectures, and then augment it using "ancestor sampling" (proposed in the second item). Throughout the assignment we will continue to work with the stochastic volatility (SV) model from the previous assignment, included here for completeness:

SV Model¶

$$\begin{equation*} x_1 \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \frac{\sigma^2}{1 - \alpha ^2}), \end{equation*}$$$$\begin{equation*} x_n \sim \mathcal{N}(\alpha x_{n-1}, \sigma^2), \end{equation*}$$$$\begin{equation*} y_n \sim \mathcal{N}(0, \beta^2\exp(x_{n})), \end{equation*}$$

for $n=1,...,T$. We will assume that the parameters $\beta$ and $\sigma^2$ are unknown, while we assume that $\alpha=0.91$.

Conjugate priors¶

We place inverse Gamma priors on the variance parameters:

\begin{align} \sigma^2 & \sim \mathcal{IG}(a=0.01,b=0.01), \\ \beta^2 & \sim \mathcal{IG}(a=0.01,b=0.01), \end{align}

where the the inverse Gamma pdf with parameters $(a,b)$ is given by \begin{equation} \mathcal{IG}(x|a,b)=\frac{b^a}{\Gamma(a)} x^{-a-1} \exp\left(-\frac{b}{x}\right) \end{equation} and $\Gamma$ is the Gamma function.

These priors are conjugate to the corresponding SV model pdf's and yield the following posteriors \begin{equation} p(\sigma^2|x_{1:T}, \alpha) = \mathcal{IG}\left(\sigma^2|a + \frac{T}{2}, b + \frac{x_1^2(1 - \alpha^2)}{2} + \frac{1}{2}\sum^{T}_{n=2} (x_n - \alpha x_{n-1})^2\right), \end{equation}

\begin{equation} p(\beta|x_{1:T}, y_{1:T}) = \mathcal{IG}\left(\beta|a + \frac{T}{2}, b + \frac{1}{2} \sum^T_{n=1}e^{-x_n}y_n^2\right) \end{equation}

2.1 Implement the Particle Gibbs¶

Implement a particle Gibbs sampler to compute the posterior distribution $p(\sigma^2,\beta^2|\alpha,y_{1:T})$. To do so, alternately sample from

  • $p(\sigma^2|\alpha,x_{1:T})$,
  • $p(\beta|x_{1:T},y_{1:T})$,
  • $p(x_{1:T}|\theta,y_{1:T})$ using conditional SMC.

To recall what a conditional SMC is, have a look at the SMC lecture slides (lecture 2 specifically), or the other resources.

Use a bootstrap particle filter (BPF) and resample at every iteration. Use the multinomial resampling scheme. Hint: read through what you need to report as stated below, before you start coding.

def LL_BPF(data, theta, K, seed):
    """data is an array of N observations
       theta is a dictionary of parameters and their values
       K is the number of particles"""
    
    np.random.seed(seed)
    cum_LL_n = []
    beta_sq = theta[0]
    alpha = theta[1]
    sigma_sq = theta[2]
    
    xgen_n = np.random.normal(loc=0, scale=(np.sqrt(sigma_sq/(1-alpha**2))), size=K) #because q(x_1) = p(x_1)
    w_n = np.repeat(1/K, K)
    cum_LL_n = np.append(cum_LL_n, np.log(norm.pdf(data[0], loc=0, scale=(np.sqrt((beta_sq)*np.exp(xgen_n)))).mean()+1e-4))

    for n in range(1, data.size):
        u = np.random.uniform(0, 1, size=K)
        prev_xgen_n = copy.deepcopy(xgen_n)
        cum_w_prev_n = np.array([w_n[:k].sum() for k in range(1,K+1)])
        a_n = [next(x[0] for x in enumerate(cum_w_prev_n) if x[1] > u[k]) for k in range(K)]
        xgen_n = np.random.normal(loc=(alpha*prev_xgen_n[a_n]), scale=(np.sqrt(sigma_sq)))
        cum_LL_n = np.append(cum_LL_n, cum_LL_n[n-1] + np.log(norm.pdf(data[n], loc=0, scale=(np.sqrt((beta_sq)*np.exp(xgen_n)))).mean()+1e-4))
        
    return(cum_LL_n)

The Particle Gibbs Implementation¶

Notes:¶

These are the things that I did slightly differently from the instructions:
- I reported $\beta^2$ here instead of $\beta$ ;
- I decided to restrict the sampled parameter values, for both $\beta^2$ and $\sigma^2$ to a lower-bound of $10^{-4}$ for the sake of avoiding numerical problems (extremely small values will produce near-zero pdf values which then lead to the undesired divisions by zero) ;
- For the same reason as above, I also imposed an upper-bound of $10^3$ for both parameters ;
- I used a gamma distribution sampler with the inverse parameters of 1/a and 1/b, instead of straight out using the inverse-gamma sampler (scipy.stats' invgamma) because the former is -again- more numerically stable. When I used the inverse-gamma sampler with the parameters a and b, it often led to an error message of 'Domain Error' and the sampling completely broke down ;
- Finally, I just took the particle with maximum weight to resample the reference's (particle K's) ancestor in the PGAS implementation, instead of trying to roll out a dice and get a number proportional to the weights of the particles; but choosing the particle with the maximum weight is still, technically speaking, taking a sample in proportion to the weights of the particle (because the one with the max weight is supposed to be chosen the most often, on average)

def generate_sv_latent_sequence(data, theta):
    beta = theta[0]
    alpha = theta[1]
    sigma_sq = theta[2]
    y_n = data
    N = data.size
    
    xgen_n = [np.random.normal(loc=0, scale=(np.sqrt(sigma_sq/(1-alpha**2))))]
    xgen_n.extend([np.random.normal(loc=(alpha*xgen_n[-1]), scale=np.sqrt(sigma_sq)) for n in range(1,N)])
    
    return(np.array(xgen_n))

def cond_SMC_kernel(data, x_ref, K, theta):
    """ *** BPF with multinomial resampling ***
       data is an array of N observations
       K is the number of particles
       theta is a dictionary of parameters and their values"""   
    
    beta_sq = theta[0]
    alpha = theta[1]
    sigma_sq = theta[2]
    y_n = data
    N = data.size
    
    a_n = {}
    xgen_n = {}
    w_n = {}

    a_n[0] = np.arange(K)
    xgen_n[0] = np.append(np.random.normal(loc=0, scale=(np.sqrt(sigma_sq/(1-alpha**2))), size=(K-1)), x_ref[0])  #because q(x_1) = p(x_1)
    w_n[0] = np.repeat(1/K, K)

    for n in range(1,N):
        u = np.random.uniform(0, 1, size=(K-1))
        cum_w_prev_n = np.append(np.array([w_n[n-1][:k].sum() for k in range(1,K)]), 1)
        a_n[n] = np.append(np.array([next(x[0] for x in enumerate(cum_w_prev_n) if x[1] > u[k]) for k in range(K-1)]), K-1)
        xgen_n[n] = np.append(np.random.normal(loc=(alpha*xgen_n[n-1][a_n[n][:-1]]), scale=np.sqrt(sigma_sq)), x_ref[n])
        w_n[n] = norm.pdf(y_n[n], loc=0, scale=np.sqrt((beta_sq)*np.exp(xgen_n[n])))
        if all(w_n[n] < 1e-4):
            w_n[n] += 1e-4
        w_n[n] /= w_n[n].sum()
        
    return(w_n, xgen_n, a_n)

def draw_from_SMC_mode(w_n, xgen_n, a_n, dead_tol):
    
    N = len(w_n)
    map_idx = np.random.randint(N-1)
    #map_idx = w_n[N-1].argmax()
    w_map = np.array([w_n[n][map_idx] for n in range(N)])
    
    w_anc = {}
    xref = np.empty(0)    
    if any(w_map < dead_tol):      #check if the path is dead somewhere
        d = 0
        dead_pos = np.where(w_map < dead_tol)[0][-1]
        a_dead = np.array([a_n[dead_pos][map_idx]])
        w_anc[0] = np.array([w_n[n][a_dead] for n in range(dead_pos)])        
        while any(w_anc[d] < dead_tol):
            d += 1
            dead_pos = np.append(dead_pos, np.array([np.where(w_anc[d-1] < dead_tol)[0][-1]]))
            a_dead = np.append(a_dead, a_n[dead_pos[d]][a_dead[d-1]])
            w_anc[d] = np.array([w_n[n][a_dead[d]] for n in range(dead_pos[d])])
        
        if not isinstance(dead_pos, np.ndarray):
            dead_pos = np.array([dead_pos])

        event_pos = np.concatenate(([N], dead_pos, [0]))
        a_hist = np.append(map_idx, a_dead)
        for i in range(event_pos.size-1):
            for n in range(event_pos[i]-1, event_pos[i+1]-1, -1):
                xref = np.append(xgen_n[n][a_hist[i]], xref)
    
    else:
        for n in range(N):
            xref = np.append(xref, xgen_n[n][map_idx])        
    
    return(xref)

def PG_kernel(data, sampled_x_ref, current_alpha, prior_hyperparams):
    
    a = prior_hyperparams[0]
    b = prior_hyperparams[1]
    y_n = data
    N = y_n.size
    
    posterior_a = a + N/2
    posterior_b_ssq = b + ((sampled_x_ref[0]**2)*(1-current_alpha**2))/2 + ((sampled_x_ref[1:N] - current_alpha*sampled_x_ref[0:N-1])**2).sum()/2
    posterior_b_bsq = b + np.dot(np.exp(-sampled_x_ref),(y_n**2))/2
    
    beta_sq, sigma_sq = gamma.rvs(a=posterior_a, scale=(1/posterior_b_bsq, 1/posterior_b_ssq))
    #beta, sigma_sq = np.random.gamma(posterior_a, scale=(1/posterior_b_bta, 1/posterior_b_ssq))
    
    flag_mini_bsq = 0
    flag_deka_bsq = 0
    flag_mini_ssq = 0
    flag_deka_ssq = 0
    if beta_sq < 1e-4:
        flag_mini_bsq += 1
        beta_sq = 1e-4
    if beta_sq > 1e3:
        flag_deka_bsq += 1
        beta_sq = 1e3
    if sigma_sq < 1e-4:
        flag_mini_ssq += 1
        sigma_sq = 1e-4
    if sigma_sq > 1e3:
        flag_deka_ssq += 1
        sigma_sq = 1e3
    
    flags = [flag_mini_bsq, flag_deka_bsq, flag_mini_ssq, flag_deka_ssq]
    
    return(beta_sq, sigma_sq, flags)

def run_particle_gibbs_chain(nr_iter, data, theta_init, K, xref_init):
    
    alpha = theta_init[1]
    theta = {0: theta_init}
    x_ref = {0: xref_init}
    a_history = {}
    xgen_history = {}
    w_history = {}
    i = 0; j = 0; k = 0; l = 0
    for iter in range(1, nr_iter):
        w_n, xgen_n, a_n = cond_SMC_kernel(data, x_ref[iter-1], K, theta[iter-1])
        xref = draw_from_SMC_mode(w_n, xgen_n, a_n, 1e-4)
        beta_sq, sigma_sq, flags,  = PG_kernel(data, xref, alpha, (.01, .01))
            
        x_ref[iter] = xref
        theta[iter] = [beta_sq, theta_init[1], sigma_sq]
        a_history[iter] = a_n
        xgen_history[iter] = xgen_n
        w_history[iter] = w_n
        i += flags[0]
        j += flags[1]
        k += flags[2]
        l += flags[3]
    
    print("Cases of diminutive beta_sq occurred in " + str(i) + " out of " + str(nr_iter) + " iterations")
    print("Cases of excessive beta_sq occurred in " + str(j) + " out of " + str(nr_iter) + " iterations")
    print("Cases of diminutive sigma_sq occurred in " + str(k) + " out of " + str(nr_iter) + " iterations")
    print("Cases of excessive sigma_sq occurred in " + str(l) + " out of " + str(nr_iter) + " iterations")
    
    return(x_ref, theta, a_history, xgen_history, w_history)

Report the approximate marginal likelihood¶

From the lecture slides, we know how to compute the following marginal likelihood

\begin{equation} p(y_{1:T}|\theta) = \int_{x_{1:T}} p(y_{1:T}|x_{1:T}, \theta) p(x_{1:T}|\theta) dx_{1:T} \approx \prod_{i=1}^T \sum_k\frac{1}{K} p(y_i|x_i^k, \theta). \end{equation}

Use the PG sampler to compute the marginal likelihood, averaged over your MCMC iterations.

Motivate why this is an approximation of the marginal likelhood, $p(y_{1:T})$. How is $p(y_{1:T})$ different from $p(y_{1:T}|\theta)$?

Answer

Taking the average of marginal likelihood per parameter, $p(y_{1:T}|\theta)$, over all the sampled parameter values is equivalent to taking $\sum_\theta p(y_{1:T}|\theta)p(\theta) = p(y_{1:T})$. It's because the relative frequency of the parameter values in the sample itself (if they are correctly sampled) approximates $p(\theta)$

Visualize the path degeneracy¶

Using the particle filter from the final MCMC iteration, plot the path degeneracy in the particle filter. Below we provide some code to help you visualize the path degeneracy. Update the code so that you can visualize the reference trajectory.

Hint: when you code your BPF, make sure to keep track of the ancestry and the inferred latent states at each time step. I.e. at each time step $n$, book keep the ancestors of the particles in the system, $k$ or $a^k$, and their corresponding $x_n$. This way you can go "backwards in time" and observe the path degeneracy.

In [63]:
def plot_trajectories(particles, ancs, T=None):
    # particles: the inferred latent states at each time step shape=(num_particles, total_time)
    # ancs: the complete ancestry shape=(num_particles, total_time)
    xs = particles
    # To plot the trajectories of the dead particles in gray
    # We have to store which ones died and save their trajectories
    dead_particles = []

    # Length of the data
    if not T:
        T = xs.shape[1]
    for i in range(T):
        xs[:,i] = list(range(1, N+1))

    for t in range(1, T):
        # It is not necessary to find the ancestor lines if no
        # particles died
        difference = np.setdiff1d(range(N), ancs[:, t])
        if len(difference) == 0:
            continue

        dead_ind = np.unique(difference)
        traj = np.zeros((len(dead_ind), t))
        ancestors = dead_ind
        for s in range(t, 0, -1):
            ancestors = ancs[ancestors, s - 1]
            traj[:, s - 1] = xs[ancestors, s - 1]

        dead_particles.append(traj)

    # Retract the actual trajectory of all particles that survived
    # until time T
    traj_survived = np.zeros((N, T))
    traj_survived[:, T-1] = xs[:, T-1]
    ancestors = range(N)
    for t in range(T, 0, -1):
        ancestors = ancs[ancestors, t - 1]
        traj_survived[:, t - 1] = xs[ancestors, t - 1]   
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(13, 6))

    for traj in dead_particles:
        for i in range(traj.shape[0]):
            ax.plot(traj[i, :], 'o-', linestyle='-',
                    color='grey', markersize=3, lw=1,
                    alpha=0.8, antialiased=True)

    for i in range(N):
        ax.plot(traj_survived[i, :], 'o-', linestyle='-',
                markeredgecolor='r',
                markerfacecolor='r',
                color='k', markersize=4, lw=1,
                alpha=1, antialiased=True)

    ax.set_xlabel('Time')
    plt.show()

def get_an_iter_epoch(a_history_iter, xgen_history_iter, w_history_iter):
    a_hist = []; xgen_hist = []; w_hist = []
    
    a_hist.append([a_history_iter[n] for n in range(N)])
    xgen_hist.append([xgen_history_iter[n] for n in range(N)])
    w_hist.append([w_history_iter[n] for n in range(N)])
    
    a_hist = np.transpose(np.squeeze(np.array(a_hist)))
    xgen_hist = np.transpose(np.squeeze(np.array(xgen_hist)))
    w_hist = np.transpose(np.squeeze(np.array(w_hist)))
    
    return(a_hist, xgen_hist, w_hist)

2.2 Implement the Particle Gibbs with Ancestral Sampling (PGAS)¶

In "Particle Gibbs with ancestor sampling" they point out that the resulting particle system in the PG sampler is undesirably biased towards the reference trajectory. This affects the path degeneracy in the way that most particles are resampled from the reference trajectory.

PGAS is a relatively small update of the PG sampler but comes with great benefits in terms of path degeneracy. Update your PG sampler above into the PGAS, repeat the following two exercises:

  • Report the approximate marginal likelihood
  • Visualize the path degeneracy

The Particle Gibbs with Ancestral Sampling (PGAS) Implementation¶

In [43]:
def cond_SMC_PGAS_kernel(data, x_ref, K, theta):
    """ *** BPF with multinomial resampling for PGAS ***
       data is an array of N observations
       K is the number of particles
       theta is a dictionary of parameters and their values"""   
    
    beta_sq = theta[0]
    alpha = theta[1]
    sigma_sq = theta[2]
    y_n = data
    N = data.size
    
    a_n = {}
    xgen_n = {}
    w_n = {}

    a_n[0] = np.arange(K)
    xgen_n[0] = np.append(np.random.normal(loc=0, scale=np.sqrt(sigma_sq/(1-alpha**2)), size=(K-1)), x_ref[0])  #because q(x_1) = p(x_1)
    w_n[0] = np.repeat(1/K, K)

    for n in range(1,N):
        u = np.random.uniform(0, 1, size=(K-1))
        cum_w_prev_n = np.append(np.array([w_n[n-1][:k].sum() for k in range(1,K)]), 1)
        wK_n = norm.pdf(x_ref[n], loc=(alpha*xgen_n[n-1]), scale=np.sqrt(sigma_sq))
        a_n[n] = np.append(np.array([next(x[0] for x in enumerate(cum_w_prev_n) if x[1] > u[k]) for k in range(K-1)]), np.array(wK_n.argmax()))
        xgen_n[n] = np.append(np.random.normal(loc=(alpha*xgen_n[n-1][a_n[n][:-1]]), scale=np.sqrt(sigma_sq)), x_ref[n])
        w_n[n] = norm.pdf(y_n[n], loc=0, scale=np.sqrt((beta_sq)*np.exp(xgen_n[n])))
        if all(w_n[n] < 1e-4):
            w_n[n] += 1e-4
        w_n[n] /= w_n[n].sum()
        
    return(w_n, xgen_n, a_n)
In [44]:
def run_PGAS_chain(nr_iter, data, theta_init, K, xref_init):
    
    alpha = theta_init[1]
    theta = {0: theta_init}
    x_ref = {0: xref_init}
    a_history = {}
    xgen_history = {}
    w_history = {}
    i = 0; j = 0; k = 0; l = 0
    for iter in range(1, nr_iter):
        w_n, xgen_n, a_n = cond_SMC_PGAS_kernel(data, x_ref[iter-1], K, theta[iter-1])
        xref = draw_from_SMC_mode(w_n, xgen_n, a_n, 1e-4)
        beta_sq, sigma_sq, flags = PG_kernel(data, xref, alpha, (.01, .01))
            
        x_ref[iter] = xref
        theta[iter] = [beta_sq, theta_init[1], sigma_sq]
        a_history[iter] = a_n
        xgen_history[iter] = xgen_n
        w_history[iter] = w_n
        i += flags[0]
        j += flags[1]
        k += flags[2]
        l += flags[3]
    
    print("Cases of diminutive beta_sq occurred in " + str(i) + " out of " + str(nr_iter) + " iterations")
    print("Cases of excessive beta_sq occurred in " + str(j) + " out of " + str(nr_iter) + " iterations")
    print("Cases of diminutive sigma_sq occurred in " + str(k) + " out of " + str(nr_iter) + " iterations")
    print("Cases of excessive sigma_sq occurred in " + str(l) + " out of " + str(nr_iter) + " iterations")
    
    return(x_ref, theta, a_history, xgen_history, w_history)

# Marginal likelihood computation
sampled_theta2 = {'beta_sq':sampled_bsq2, 'sigma_sq':sampled_ssq2}
theta_sets2 = [(sampled_theta2['beta_sq'][s], .91, sampled_theta2['sigma_sq'][s]) for s in range(sampled_theta2['beta_sq'].size)]

t0 = time.time()

sum_lik_pair2 = 0
count_bad_exp2 = 0
for theta in theta_sets2:
    exponent = LL_BPF(sv_obs, theta, K, seed=173710)[-1]  #ll at the last time step N
    if np.isnan(np.array(exponent)):
        count_bad_exp2 += 1
        continue
    
    sum_lik_pair2 += np.exp(exponent)

marg_lik2 = sum_lik_pair2/(len(theta_sets2)-count_bad_exp2)

t1 = time.time()
total_time = t1 - t0
warnings.filterwarnings(action='once')
print('total time is', total_time//3600, 'hour', (total_time%3600)//60, 'minute', (total_time%3600)%60, 'seconds')
print('while catching ' + str(count_bad_exp2) + ' bad exponent(s)')
